abstract = {The use of statistical methods to analyze large databases of text has been useful in unveiling$\backslash$n patterns of human behavior and establishing historical links between cultures and languages. In this$\backslash$n study, we identified literary movements by treating books published from 1590 to 1922 as complex$\backslash$n networks, whose metrics were analyzed with multivariate techniques to generate six clusters of$\backslash$n books. The latter correspond to time periods coinciding with relevant literary movements over the$\backslash$n last five centuries. The most important factor contributing to the distinctions between different$\backslash$n literary styles was the average shortest path length, in particular the asymmetry of its$\backslash$n distribution. Furthermore, over time there has emerged a trend toward larger average shortest path$\backslash$n lengths, which is correlated with increased syntactic complexity, and a more uniform use of the$\backslash$n words reflected in a smaller power-law coefficient for the distribution of word frequency. Changes$\backslash$n in literary style were also found to be driven by opposition to earlier writing styles, as revealed$\backslash$n by the analysis performed with geometrical concepts. The approaches adopted here are generic and may$\backslash$n be extended to analyze a number of features of languages and cultures.},
